title: Ben Stokes puts Ashes on back burner to focus on England‚Äôs here and now
description: England captain admits he ‚Äòspoke a little too much‚Äô about Australia showdown instead of New Zealand and India TestsEngland are about to complete their busiest year of Test cricket with Ben Stokes encouraged by the overhaul in personnel that has taken place. Although the captain has a small regret from this period: publicly discussing the next Ashes series. The third Test against New Zealand that starts in Hamilton on Saturday (10pm Friday UK) will be England‚Äôs 17th in 2024, matching only their fixture list in 2016 by way of volume. That year saw a jaded Alastair Cook quit the captaincy but while Stokes called 2024 ‚Äúa long, tough slog‚Äù, the 33-year-old completes it looking personally rejuvenated.The same goes for a side that finished 2023 with an average age of 32 and has since shaved that figure by nearly five years. The retirements of Jimmy Anderson, Stuart Broad and Moeen Ali ‚Äì plus the decision to move on from Jonny Bairstow ‚Äì account for much of this shift, while the subsequent arrivals of Gus Atkinson, Brydon Carse, Jamie Smith and Shoaib Bashir have largely vindicated the policy also. Ordering an all-time great such as Anderson to step aside at the start of the summer was not straightforward, however, and took some explaining publicly. And it was here where Stokes found himself using the 2025-26 Ashes ‚Äì and the likelihood a seamer already in his forties would not make it that far ‚Äì as the overriding justification.
